text: Marvel popularized The Cinematic Universe. Making solo superhero movies and putting them all together for the first time in one movie with The Avengers. Now DC has their own although not nearly as successful. Universal pictures wants to build their own Cinematic Universe with all the classic monsters.   Dracula, Frankenstein, Dr. Jekyll, The Wolfman, etc. And the first movie they're starting with is The Mummy. I've really liked everything I've seen so far and this new trailer is no exception. I'm looking forward to it and I hope it's the beginning of another great cinematic universe.

text: Will I watch it, of course I will. Most movies I have seen with Tom Cruise tends to be fairly good, he picks good scripts for the most part.  But perhaps it is the nostalgic kid in me that just can't help but feel like this is missing something. I know this is not a remake of the previous mummy movies, it is more a complete reboot with a new universe. But what I loved about the first two mummy movies at least was that sense of adventure, the mystery, the amazing chemistry of the cast and just the pure charm it had. And I don't like that they set it in current time instead of the 1920s as it had a lot to do with the sense of adventure it had. I don't get that feeling from this trailer, it seems to be way more serious and way darker.   But who knows, it might still be a great movie. I guess I just have to try and forget the love I have for the previous films and give this one a chance.

Sadly, I think the trailer showed a bit too much of the movie, as as per usual, gave away or spoiled parts that are most likely set piece moments in the final film. text: Should the actress be black? Due to the shot of her looking at the great pyramids we could safely assume that this takes place after the Old Kingdom of Egypt, and the fact that every metal object is bronze (like how well preserved the sarcophagas is) it would be long before the Ptolemaic dynasty (European rulers, Macedonian to be precise) so she probably would be African, presumably, of course, since it's pretty damn hard to be sure about people that lived 5k years ago.   But how would she have looked, even if we know for sure that she's African, we have no clue really, since again it's really hard to reconstruct how ancient people look like. My guess is that the actress choice points to the most famous Egyptian female: Cleopetra VII, who of course is Macedonian in origin.  BUT, this is a film about how Egyptian mummies turn evil and fuck up shit, so i doubt that cultural sensitivity would be at the top of their concerns  And to be honest, this looks dumb, and not in a goofy funny way, but in a "taking everything way too serious" way, so im not paying to see it any time soon
